| /24  | 255.255.255.0   | 1                   | 0 â€“ 255                            | 254                 | Default class C subnet            |
| /25  | 255.255.255.128 | 2                   | 0 â€“ 127 / 128 â€“ 255                | 126                 | Splits /24 in half                |
| /26  | 255.255.255.192 | 4                   | 0â€“63 / 64â€“127 / 128â€“191 / 192â€“255  | 62                  | 4 subnets of 64 IPs               |
| /27  | 255.255.255.224 | 8                   | 0â€“31 / 32â€“63 â€¦ 224â€“255             | 30                  | 8 subnets of 32 IPs               |
| /28  | 255.255.255.240 | 16                  | 0â€“15 / 16â€“31 â€¦ 240â€“255             | 14                  | Good for small LANs               |
| /29  | 255.255.255.248 | 32                  | 0â€“7 / 8â€“15 â€¦ 248â€“255               | 6                   | Common for point-to-point links   |
| /30  | 255.255.255.252 | 64                  | 0â€“3 / 4â€“7 â€¦ 252â€“255                | 2                   | Only 2 hosts, perfect for routers |
| /31  | 255.255.255.254 | 128                 | 0â€“1 / 2â€“3 â€¦ 254â€“255                | 2                   | **Both IPs usable!** (RFC 3021)   |
| /32  | 255.255.255.255 | 256 (single IPs)    | One IP only                        | 0                   | Used for loopback or host routes  |

ðŸ§ NBðŸ§ 
Network address = First IP of subnet (reserved)	
Broadcast address = Last IP of subnet (reserved)
Usable IPs = Total - 2 (except /31 where both are usable)
/32 is not a subnet, just a single IP (no range)
